comment: This is a good time for a recovery snack. High protein content is recommended, perhaps some natural sources of potassium as well (such as bananas or yogurt). Plant-based protein shakes are recommended. Blend in your favorite dark leafy greens.
title: Eat Greens

comment:
Your body is now primed for sports. Your hand-eye coordination is at its peak, your reaction time is now the fastest it will be all day, and your cardiovascular efficiency and muscle strength are approaching maximum. ðª

Use this time to fully engage in your favorite sport or physical activity. Make sure you sweat, and whatever you choose feels good and is something you might aspire to do every day.

Sharing this time with a friend or family member is a bonus.
title: Move

comment:
Ideally we go to sleep approximately one to two hours after sunset, around the time our ancestors may have regularly gone to sleep before artificial light.

Melatonin secretion has begun, which means your sleep hormone is telling the body to wrap up for the night. Your digestive system should now be suppressed.
title: Dreams

comment:
A large breakfast is the healthiest way to structure your meal plan.

Research from Harvard's School of Public Health and the Salk Institute, among others, shows that breakfast is indeed the most important meal of the day. This is the time to pack in your calories, absorb healthy sources of protein (ideally from plants) and get complex carbohydrates into your system (from whole grains, for example).

Most of us pack in our calories at nighttime, for dinner or late at night with midnight snacks. This is the worst thing we can do for ourselves from an evolutionary perspective.

Our body was designed to digest foods during the day, and our digestive system actually tries to shut off at night. So eating in the morning maximizes our ability to digest foods appropriately, and not sustain high blood sugar levels for example. In fact, studies from Salk show that eating the SAME diet with the SAME number of calories during our biological daytime minimizes weight gain and chances for developing chronic disease.

An old proverb says, "Eat breakfast like a king, lunch like a prince and dinner like a pauper." Science is proving this is sound advice.
title: Eat

comment:
The sun may be setting now. Time to plan how to decelerate your day.

This is a period for healthy, substantive eating. Focus should be on dark greens, vegetables, fruits and salads. Add nuts or beans for further nourishment.

This will be your last meal of the day, since your body is getting ready to shut down its digestive processes in one to two hours. If you really get hungry after this point, stick to non-caffeinated herbal hot teas, small amounts of nuts and/or tiny bits of dark chocolate.
title: Healthy Eats

comment:
Now is the time to handle social requirements for work, such as meetings, email correspondence or phone calls. 

As the day progresses, we become less diligent at work requiring high degrees of concentration in social isolation. We are naturally blossoming into the day, and craving positive social contact at this point is normal.
title: Meeting

comment:
Your alertness levels and cognitive capabilities are at a daytime high.

This is the best time in your day for deep work. Shut off the social media, email and mindless distractions and tasks. Focus on deep reading, writing, calculating or your highest creative or constructive goals for the day.

Many cite a peak of will power during this time. While this may be hard to measure, objectively we know that alertness levels are now at their highest. Studies demonstrate peak abilities to solve puzzles, organize thoughts and think through complex mathematics during this time.

Our prefrontal cortex, the most evolved part of our brain, is receiving its highest period of blood flow and is most active during this time. Take advantage of it, and make a habit out of doing so.
title: Study

comment:
You've reached your highest body temperature for the day. It's time to unwind with your loved ones and prep for bed. ð´

Hopefully your dinner was shared with loved ones, and you are ready to decline your day. Spend time with those that matter most to you, because strong relationships based on love, support and compassion are the deepest source of nourishment we can find.

At this point, your body has already hit its highest temperature point for the day, and is now in a gradual decline... this means your sleep drive is increasing. Anticipate your upcoming melatonin release by closing out the evening with a preferred nighttime ritual. Suggestions include dimming the lights, turning off all glowing screens, sealing the curtains and keeping a cool temperature in the bedroom.
title: Gratitude

comment:
Getting early morning sunlight is the best way to synchronize your body's rhythm with your solar environment.

Most of us live predominantly indoor lives.

Slap on some suntan lotion and greet the sun today. Go for a small walk around the block or at a nearby park. Bring a loved one with you.

Sunlight transfers through our optic nerves to the "SCN", or suprachiasmatic nucleus. This is our "master clock" or pacemaker, responsible for coordinating all our body's rhythms. Think of it as the conductor in a magnificent orchestra. To get your body in harmony today, start with the conductor by letting her know that this is the beginning of your day.

Practically speaking, it will reset your melatonin cycle so it kicks back in at the appropriate time in the late evening... this is your body's natural rhythm at play.

Going for a walk magnifies the robustness of this circadian response. By being active in the morning, you are telling your musculoskeletal system that the day has begun. A body in motion stays in motion, and by the time late evening comes around you'll be appropriately yawning and sleepy...
title: Get outside

comment:
The sun is rising. Your blood pressure is experiencing it's fastest rise as cortisol peaks and melatonin drops.

Our evolutionary biology is programmed to rise with the sun. Around this time, our blood pressure spikes as we respond to natural flushes of cortisol through our cardiovascular system. Our heart rate rises as it anticipates our activities for the day.

Given early mornings can be a period of peak activity for our cardiovascular system, and so many of us suffer from stress, now is the best time to practice your favorite stress management technique.

Whether it's deep breathing exercises, meditation, yoga, prayer, visualization, goal-setting, gardening or even playing with the kids. It's good to train yourself to approach each day with a smile, and not let our to-do's become a gray cloud.
title: Plan my day

comment: Free time. Listen to your body clock and do what you need to do.
title: Flow

comment:
Listen to your body clock.

Is this a time to catch up on work? Or spend time with friends or family?

Maybe you need a nap after a long day this morning or yesterday...

Your primary goal at this time is to visualize your upcoming workout, and make sure all the materials you need for that activity are ready-to-go. Need gym shoes? Check. Yoga mat? Check.
title: Jammin'

comment:
Time for a light lunch. Hopefully you're well satiated from a large, healthy breakfast.

Try to consume fresh fruits and vegetables, and healthy sources of complex carbohydrates to keep sustained energy for the day. No soda, rather drink lots of water and stay hydrated. A good pace is to aim for eight cups of water per day.

Avoid fatty foods and oils, as those will take longer to digest and slow you down. Right now your goal should be to prep your body for an afternoon workout. We will need to plan one to two hours to digest your lunch... so keep it light. Get hydrated, focus on lean, plant-based sources of protein.

And start imagining how awesome your 2PM workout will be...
title: Eat Greens
